---
import { BOHR_SEMVER } from "@/data/bohr-root-version"
import {
  BOHR_INSTALL_PS1_URL,
  BOHR_INSTALL_SH_URL,
  BOHR_INSTALL_SKILLS_PS1_URL,
  BOHR_INSTALL_SKILLS_SH_URL,
} from "@/data/site-urls"
---

<p>
  Bohr AI ships as a standalone runtime bundle for supported macOS, Linux, and Windows machines. The
  installer downloads a prebuilt native bundle, so you do not need to preinstall Node.js just to run Bohr.
</p>

<p>
  You do not need to deploy a running web app before changing these commands. What matters is that the
  installer scripts and release bundles are published at reachable URLs.
</p>

<h2 id="one-line-installer-recommended">One-line installer (recommended)</h2>

<p>On <strong>macOS or Linux</strong>, open a terminal and run:</p>

<pre><code>{`curl -fsSL ${BOHR_INSTALL_SH_URL} | bash`}</code></pre>

<p>
  The installer detects your OS and architecture automatically. On macOS it supports both Intel and Apple
  Silicon. On Linux it supports x64 and arm64. The launcher is installed to <code>~/.local/bin</code>, the
  bundled runtime is unpacked into <code>~/.local/share/bohr</code>, and your <code>PATH</code> is updated
  when needed.
</p>

<p>
  If you previously installed Bohr AI through a package manager and still see local Node.js errors after a
  curl install, your shell is probably still resolving the older global binary first. Run <code>which -a bohr</code>,
  then <code>hash -r</code>, or launch the standalone shim directly with <code>~/.local/bin/bohr</code>.
</p>

<p>On <strong>Windows</strong>, open PowerShell and run:</p>

<pre><code>{`irm ${BOHR_INSTALL_PS1_URL} | iex`}</code></pre>

<p>
  This installs the Windows runtime bundle under <code>%LOCALAPPDATA%\Programs\bohr</code>, adds its launcher
  to your user <code>PATH</code>, and lets you re-run the installer at any time to update.
</p>

<p>
  Bohr currently targets supported desktop and server platforms. iOS and Android are not standalone CLI
  targets for this installer flow.
</p>

<h2 id="internal-client-deployments">Internal client deployments</h2>

<p>
  If you are deploying Bohr inside a client environment, treat the upstream GitHub commands as the default
  fallback, not the final distribution URLs. The repo supports overriding hosting and release endpoints with
  deployment variables such as:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><code>PUBLIC_BOHR_SITE_URL</code></li>
  <li><code>PUBLIC_BOHR_INSTALL_BASE_URL</code></li>
  <li><code>BOHR_RELEASES_LATEST_URL</code></li>
  <li><code>BOHR_INSTALL_BASE_URL</code></li>
  <li><code>BOHR_REPO_ARCHIVE_BASE_URL</code></li>
</ul>

<p>
  Set those before building the website or publishing installers so the same codebase can point at the
  client's own domain, artifact store, or internal web server.
</p>

<h2 id="updating-the-standalone-app">Updating the standalone app</h2>

<p>
  To update the standalone Bohr AI app on macOS, Linux, or Windows, rerun the installer you originally used.
  That replaces the downloaded runtime bundle with the latest tagged release.
</p>

<p>
  <code>bohr update</code> is different: it updates installed Pi packages inside Bohr AI's environment, not
  the standalone app bundle itself.
</p>

<h2 id="skills-only">Skills only</h2>

<p>If you only want Bohr AI research skills and not the full terminal runtime, install the skill library separately.</p>

<p>For a user-level install into <code>~/.codex/skills/bohr</code>:</p>

<pre><code>{`curl -fsSL ${BOHR_INSTALL_SKILLS_SH_URL} | bash`}</code></pre>

<p>For a repo-local install into <code>.agents/skills/bohr</code> under the current repository:</p>

<pre><code>{`curl -fsSL ${BOHR_INSTALL_SKILLS_SH_URL} | bash -s -- --repo`}</code></pre>

<p>On Windows, install the skills into your Codex skill directory:</p>

<pre><code>{`irm ${BOHR_INSTALL_SKILLS_PS1_URL} | iex`}</code></pre>

<p>Or install them repo-locally:</p>

<pre><code>{`& ([scriptblock]::Create((irm ${BOHR_INSTALL_SKILLS_PS1_URL}))) -Scope Repo`}</code></pre>

<p>
  These installers download the bundled <code>skills/</code> and <code>prompts/</code> trees plus the repo
  guidance files referenced by those skills. They do not install the Bohr AI terminal, bundled Node runtime,
  auth storage, or Pi packages.
</p>

<h2 id="pinned-releases">Pinned releases</h2>

<p>The one-line installer already targets the latest tagged release. To pin an exact version, pass it explicitly:</p>

<pre><code>{`curl -fsSL ${BOHR_INSTALL_SH_URL} | bash -s -- ${BOHR_SEMVER}`}</code></pre>

<p>On Windows:</p>

<pre><code>{`& ([scriptblock]::Create((irm ${BOHR_INSTALL_PS1_URL}))) -Version ${BOHR_SEMVER}`}</code></pre>

<h2 id="post-install-setup">Post-install setup</h2>

<p>After installation, run the guided setup wizard to configure your model provider and API keys:</p>

<pre><code>bohr setup</code></pre>

<p>
  This walks you through selecting a default model, authenticating with your provider, and optionally
  installing extra packages for features like web search and document preview. See the
  <a href="/docs/getting-started/setup">Setup guide</a> for a detailed walkthrough.
</p>

<h2 id="verifying-the-installation">Verifying the installation</h2>

<p>Confirm Bohr AI is installed and accessible:</p>

<pre><code>bohr --version</code></pre>

<p>
  If you see a version number, you are ready to go. Run <code>bohr doctor</code> at any time to diagnose
  configuration issues, missing dependencies, or authentication problems.
</p>

<h2 id="local-development">Local development</h2>

<p>For contributing or running Bohr AI from source:</p>

<pre><code>{`git clone https://github.com/Dhruvil7694/BohrAI.git
cd BohrAI
nvm use || nvm install
npm install
npm start`}</code></pre>
